const QUESTIONS_CHFI_C2 = [
  { id:70301, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the smallest addressable unit of data on a traditional hard disk drive platter?", options:["A sector, which classically holds 512 bytes or 4096 bytes on advanced format drives today","A cluster, the grouping that the file system uses to allocate file storage space areas","A cylinder, comprising all tracks at the same radius across every platter surface present","A track, a single concentric ring of data on one side of one spinning disk platter here"], correct:0, explanation:"A sector is the smallest physically addressable unit on an HDD. A cluster is a file-system allocation grouping, not a hardware-level unit." },
  { id:70302, domain:3, level:1, question:"What term describes the unused space between the end of a file and the end of its last cluster?", options:["RAM slack appended by the operating system into the partially filled final disk sector here","File slack, the leftover area in the last cluster not used by the actual stored file data","Swap space reserved on the disk by the OS for virtual memory paging operations at runtime","Unallocated space that the file system marks as entirely available for new files to use"], correct:1, explanation:"File slack is leftover space in the last cluster a file occupies. Unallocated space is wholly free, not tied to a specific file's tail." },
  { id:70303, domain:3, level:1, question:"On magnetic hard drives, what does the term cluster refer to?", options:["A physical grouping of platters mounted on a single spindle inside the drive housing unit","The arc-shaped region under the read/write head during a single rotation of the spinning disk","The smallest unit of disk allocation used by the file system, made of one or more sectors","A reserved firmware area used to remap sectors that the drive detects as defective over time"], correct:2, explanation:"A cluster is the file system's minimum allocation unit, made of one or more sectors. The defect-remap area is the drive's spare sector pool, unrelated." },
  { id:70304, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why does forensic analysis of SSDs differ fundamentally from HDD analysis?", options:["SSDs rotate faster, so timing-based recovery of magnetic remanence becomes far less reliable","SSDs store data optically, requiring laser-based readers rather than standard write blockers","SSDs always encrypt every block in hardware, so plaintext recovery is simply impossible now","SSDs use the TRIM command and wear leveling, which can erase deleted data before imaging it"], correct:3, explanation:"TRIM and wear leveling can purge deleted blocks quickly, complicating recovery. SSDs are not optical and not all self-encrypt by default." },
  { id:70305, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of the Host Protected Area on a hard disk?", options:["A hidden region set via SET MAX ADDRESS that is not visible to the normal operating system","A cached buffer where the drive temporarily stores writes before committing them to platters","The boot sector region that stores the master boot record and the partition table entries","A spare area the drive uses transparently to replace sectors that have gone bad over time"], correct:0, explanation:"The HPA is a hidden area set with SET MAX ADDRESS, invisible to the normal OS. The bad-sector replacement region is the reallocation pool, a different concept." },
  { id:70306, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is a Device Configuration Overlay on an ATA drive?", options:["A logging mechanism that records every read and write transaction the drive has performed","A feature letting the manufacturer hide or modify the apparent capacity and features of a drive","An encryption layer that the drive applies automatically to all sectors without any key set overall","A diagnostic partition that vendors install to run self-tests on the storage hardware unit"], correct:1, explanation:"A DCO lets a manufacturer hide capacity or disable features. It is not a log of all I/O nor a built-in encryption layer." },
  { id:70307, domain:3, level:2, question:"Where is the Master Boot Record located on a disk that uses MBR partitioning?", options:["In the last sector of the first partition, immediately following the volume boot record code","Spread across the first sixty-three sectors that are reserved ahead of the first partition area","In the first sector of the disk, logical block address zero, which is the very first 512 bytes","In a dedicated hidden track at the outer edge of the platter where the firmware also resides"], correct:2, explanation:"The MBR sits in the first sector, LBA 0. It is not in the last sector of a partition nor spread across the reserved track region." },
  { id:70308, domain:3, level:2, question:"How many primary partitions does the classic MBR partitioning scheme support?", options:["Up to one hundred twenty-eight primary partitions thanks to its very large entry table size overall","Exactly two primary partitions, one bootable and one reserved for system recovery data only","An unlimited number of primary partitions because the table can be chained indefinitely now","Up to four primary partitions, or three primary partitions plus one extended partition total"], correct:3, explanation:"MBR supports four primary partitions, or three primary plus one extended. The 128-partition figure describes GPT, not MBR." },
  { id:70309, domain:3, level:2, question:"What advantage does GPT offer over MBR for large modern disks?", options:["GPT supports disks larger than 2 TB and stores backup partition table copies for redundancy","GPT compresses every partition automatically, halving the storage that user data consumes","GPT eliminates the need for any boot loader because firmware reads files directly from it","GPT encrypts partition contents by default using a key derived from the disk serial number overall"], correct:0, explanation:"GPT handles disks over 2 TB and keeps a backup table at the disk's end. It does not compress or auto-encrypt partitions." },
  { id:70310, domain:3, level:2, question:"In the GPT scheme, what is the role of the protective MBR at LBA 0?", options:["It stores the actual GPT partition entries so legacy systems can still mount the partitions","It prevents older MBR-only tools from seeing the disk as empty and overwriting GPT structures","It contains the encryption keys that unlock each of the GPT partitions during the system boot","It holds a second copy of the operating system kernel used when the primary copy fails badly"], correct:1, explanation:"The protective MBR makes legacy tools see one whole-disk partition, preventing accidental overwrite. It does not store GPT entries, keys, or a kernel." },
  { id:70311, domain:3, level:2, question:"In the FAT file system, what does the File Allocation Table itself primarily track?", options:["The full directory tree with every file name, permission set, and security descriptor present overall","Only the timestamps and the attribute bytes for files stored within the disk's root directory","The chain of clusters allocated to each file and which clusters are free, bad, or end-of-chain","The journal of pending metadata transactions awaiting commit after an unexpected power loss"], correct:2, explanation:"The FAT maps cluster chains and marks free, bad, and EOF clusters. FAT keeps no journal and does not store full security descriptors." },
  { id:70312, domain:3, level:2, question:"When a file is deleted on a FAT file system, what typically happens to its directory entry?", options:["The entire directory entry is immediately overwritten with zeros to prevent any later recovery","The entry is moved into an encrypted recycle area that only the system account can later open","The entry is copied to the FAT backup table and the original directory slot is left untouched","The first character of the file name is replaced with marker byte 0xE5 and the clusters freed"], correct:3, explanation:"FAT marks deletion by setting the first name byte to 0xE5 and freeing the chain. The data and most of the entry persist, enabling recovery; nothing is zeroed." },
  { id:70313, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the maximum file size supported by the FAT32 file system?", options:["4 GB minus one byte, because the file size field is a 32-bit value measured in single bytes","2 TB minus one byte, matching the largest volume that FAT32 is able to address overall here","16 EB, the same theoretical ceiling that the NTFS file system is able to provide to its users","Exactly 64 GB, a hard cap imposed to keep the allocation table small enough for floppy disks"], correct:0, explanation:"FAT32 caps individual files at 4 GB minus one byte due to its 32-bit size field. The TB and EB figures apply to volumes or NTFS, not FAT32 file size." },
  { id:70314, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is a key forensic advantage of exFAT over FAT32 for modern removable media?", options:["exFAT encrypts every file by default, protecting data that is stored on lost USB flash drives","exFAT removes the 4 GB per-file limit, allowing large video and image files on flash media","exFAT keeps a full transactional journal identical to the one NTFS maintains for recovery","exFAT compresses all stored data automatically, roughly doubling effective drive capacity"], correct:1, explanation:"exFAT lifts FAT32's 4 GB file limit, suiting large media files. It is not encrypted, fully journaled, or auto-compressing by default." },
  { id:70315, domain:3, level:3, question:"What central NTFS structure stores a record for every file and directory on the volume?", options:["The File Allocation Table, a flat list mapping every cluster to a numbered file on the volume","The volume boot record, which enumerates all files sequentially from the disk's first sector","The Master File Table, where each record describes one file's attributes and its data runs","The superblock, a fixed structure cataloguing every inode and free block across the partition"], correct:2, explanation:"NTFS centers on the MFT, one record per file/directory. The FAT and superblock belong to FAT and ext file systems, respectively." },
  { id:70316, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is an NTFS Alternate Data Stream and why is it relevant to forensics?", options:["A backup copy of the MFT that NTFS keeps so the volume can recover from a corruption event","A compression stream NTFS uses to shrink large files transparently as they are written to disk","A logging stream that records who opened each file along with the exact time of the access","An extra named data stream attached to a file that can hide data invisible to normal listings"], correct:3, explanation:"ADS lets extra named streams ride along with a file, a common data-hiding technique. The MFT mirror and compression are separate NTFS features." },
  { id:70317, domain:3, level:3, question:"For very small files, how does NTFS often store the file's data efficiently?", options:["Resident in the MFT record itself, so no separate clusters are allocated for tiny file contents","In the volume's slack space, scattered across whatever unused sector tails happen to be free","Inside the $Bitmap metadata file, alongside the map of allocated and free clusters on a volume","In the page file, where the OS keeps frequently used small files for quick later access on disk"], correct:0, explanation:"NTFS can store small files resident inside the MFT record. Slack space, $Bitmap, and the page file are not used for normal resident storage." },
  { id:70318, domain:3, level:3, question:"Within an NTFS MFT record, which attribute commonly holds the file's MAC timestamps?", options:["$DATA, the attribute that exclusively stores the file's actual content bytes on the volume here","$STANDARD_INFORMATION, and also $FILE_NAME, both carrying create, modify, and access times","$BITMAP, which tracks which clusters in the volume are currently allocated versus free for use","$SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR, holding only the ownership and the permission information for the file"], correct:1, explanation:"MAC timestamps live in $STANDARD_INFORMATION and $FILE_NAME. $DATA holds content, $BITMAP tracks clusters, and the security descriptor holds permissions." },
  { id:70319, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is comparing $STANDARD_INFORMATION and $FILE_NAME timestamps useful to investigators?", options:["It lets the examiner recover the file's content from the redundant copies that NTFS keeps stored","It confirms the disk's serial number by cross-checking the two attribute hash signatures present","Discrepancies can reveal timestamp tampering, since some anti-forensic tools alter only one set","It reveals the BitLocker recovery key embedded between the two timestamp attribute data blocks"], correct:2, explanation:"Many timestomping tools alter $STANDARD_INFORMATION but not $FILE_NAME, so mismatches expose tampering. The other options misdescribe these attributes." },
  { id:70320, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does the NTFS $LogFile metadata file provide?", options:["A complete list of every user password hash for the accounts that exist on the local machine","An index of all deleted files so they can always be restored to their original disk locations overall","A mirror of the entire $DATA content of every file for redundancy against a disk read failure","A transactional journal of metadata changes enabling consistency recovery after a system crash"], correct:3, explanation:"$LogFile journals metadata changes for crash recovery. It is not a password store, deleted-file index, or content mirror." },
  { id:70321, domain:3, level:1, question:"In the ext family of Linux file systems, what does an inode store?", options:["File metadata such as permissions, ownership, timestamps, and pointers to the file's data blocks","The human-readable file name together with the parent directory path for every file present here","A journaled list of pending writes that the kernel must flush before the next periodic disk sync","The boot loader code and partition table that the BIOS reads at the very start of system startup"], correct:0, explanation:"An inode holds metadata and block pointers but not the file name, which lives in the directory entry. It is not the boot loader or journal." },
  { id:70322, domain:3, level:1, question:"What capability does ext3 add compared with ext2?", options:["Built-in transparent encryption of every file using a per-user key stored in the volume superblock","Journaling, which records metadata changes to allow faster and safer recovery after a crash here","Support for files larger than 16 exabytes by widening every single block pointer out to 128 bits","Automatic deduplication that removes identical data blocks to save space across the whole volume"], correct:1, explanation:"ext3 introduced journaling over ext2. It did not add built-in encryption, exabyte files, or deduplication as defining features." },
  { id:70323, domain:3, level:1, question:"Where does a Linux ext file system keep the parameters describing the whole volume?", options:["The first inode, number one, which by convention catalogs every other inode in the whole system overall","The master boot record, shared with the partition table at the very start of the physical disk","The superblock, which records block size, total inode and block counts, and the volume state flag","The journal file, which doubles as the authoritative record of the volume-wide configuration"], correct:2, explanation:"The superblock stores volume-wide parameters. Inode one is reserved/bad-block related, the MBR is partition-level, and the journal logs transactions." },
  { id:70324, domain:3, level:1, question:"What modern Apple file system replaced HFS+ as the default starting with macOS High Sierra?", options:["exFAT, adopted because it removed file-size limits and is supported across many other platforms","ZFS, the high-integrity file system that Apple licensed and shipped on all of its desktop machines","NTFS, which Apple adopted to improve interoperability with Windows-based corporate networks now","APFS, the Apple File System, designed with strong support for SSDs, snapshots, and encryption"], correct:3, explanation:"APFS replaced HFS+ from High Sierra onward. Apple did not ship ZFS broadly, nor adopt exFAT or NTFS as the macOS default." },
  { id:70325, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which feature is native to APFS and useful when reconstructing prior file states?", options:["Snapshots, point-in-time read-only views of the file system that can preserve the earlier data","A Host Protected Area that hides earlier file versions from the operating system entirely here","Alternate data streams that attach hidden historical copies to each individual file present now","A FAT-style allocation table chaining each prior version of a file through cluster pointers here"], correct:0, explanation:"APFS supports snapshots for point-in-time views. HPA, ADS, and FAT chains belong to other technologies, not APFS versioning." },
  { id:70326, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which RAID level stripes data across disks with no redundancy, maximizing speed and capacity?", options:["RAID 1, which mirrors every block to a second disk so all data survives one disk failure event","RAID 0, which offers no fault tolerance, so losing any single disk loses the entire array data","RAID 5, which distributes parity across disks so the array tolerates one disk failing at a time","RAID 6, which keeps dual parity so the array survives two simultaneous disk failures quite safely"], correct:1, explanation:"RAID 0 stripes without redundancy. RAID 1 mirrors, and RAID 5/6 use parity, all of which provide some fault tolerance unlike RAID 0." },
  { id:70327, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which RAID level mirrors identical data onto two or more drives for redundancy?", options:["RAID 0, where data is split across drives with no copy kept anywhere for any fault tolerance at all","RAID 5, where a single rotating parity block is distributed across all of the member disks present","RAID 1, where each drive holds a full copy so the array survives the loss of a single member disk","JBOD, where drives are simply concatenated into one large volume without any redundancy provided"], correct:2, explanation:"RAID 1 mirrors data for redundancy. RAID 0 and JBOD provide none, and RAID 5 uses distributed parity rather than full mirroring." },
  { id:70328, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why can RAID arrays complicate forensic acquisition?", options:["RAID disks always encrypt their contents, requiring the controller's key before any imaging starts","RAID controllers physically destroy data when a disk is removed from the powered-off array unit","RAID volumes can only be imaged while the array is mounted and actively serving live user traffic","Data is split across multiple disks, so the examiner must reconstruct the array to read the files"], correct:3, explanation:"Striped/parity RAID spreads data across disks, so the array logic must be reconstructed. RAID does not inherently encrypt or self-destruct on removal." },
  { id:70329, domain:3, level:2, question:"In the legacy BIOS boot process, what does the BIOS hand control to first on the boot disk?", options:["The Master Boot Record code in the first sector, which then loads the volume boot record next","The operating system kernel directly, bypassing any intermediate boot loader stages entirely here","The GPT header at LBA 1, reading partition entries before any executable code is run at all here","The page file, from which it restores the previous suspended session of the operating system now"], correct:0, explanation:"BIOS executes the MBR boot code first, which chains to the VBR. It does not jump straight to the kernel or read GPT in legacy mode." },
  { id:70330, domain:3, level:2, question:"What firmware standard has largely replaced legacy BIOS and works natively with GPT?", options:["ACPI, the standard that solely governs how the system manages power states and device wakeups","UEFI, which supports larger disks, secure boot, and reads boot loaders from an EFI partition","POST, the routine that merely tests the hardware components before any operating system loads","SMBIOS, a table format describing hardware inventory that the OS queries after it has booted"], correct:1, explanation:"UEFI replaced legacy BIOS and pairs with GPT. ACPI handles power, POST tests hardware, and SMBIOS is an inventory table, none of which boot the system." },
  { id:70331, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the primary purpose of a hardware write blocker during acquisition?", options:["To accelerate imaging by caching the suspect drive's contents in fast volatile memory first here","To encrypt the forensic image as it is written so the evidence cannot be tampered with any later","To allow read access to the suspect drive while preventing any writes that would alter evidence","To convert the suspect drive's file system into a format the examiner's tools can readily parse"], correct:2, explanation:"A write blocker permits reads while blocking writes to preserve the original. It does not encrypt, convert file systems, or merely cache for speed." },
  { id:70332, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is a bit-stream forensic image of a disk?", options:["A copy of only the active files and folders, omitting deleted data and unused disk regions entirely overall","A compressed archive of the user's documents folder created by the operating system backup tool","A snapshot of the disk's partition table alone, used to recreate the layout on a fresh new drive","An exact bit-for-bit copy of the entire drive, including slack and unallocated space, not just files"], correct:3, explanation:"A bit-stream image duplicates every bit, including slack and unallocated areas. A logical/file copy or partition-only snapshot omits much recoverable data." },
  { id:70333, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why are cryptographic hashes such as MD5 or SHA-256 computed during forensic imaging?", options:["To verify the image is an exact copy and to prove the evidence was not altered afterward at all","To compress the disk image so it occupies far less space on the examiner's storage media drive overall","To encrypt the contents of the image so only authorized investigators can later open the file","To index every file by content so keyword searches across the image run very much more quickly"], correct:0, explanation:"Hashes verify integrity and prove the image is unchanged. Hashing neither compresses, encrypts, nor indexes the data for search." },
  { id:70334, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does the E01 EnCase Evidence forensic image format provide beyond raw dd images?", options:["A live read-write mount that lets investigators edit the suspect data inside the image file itself","Embedded metadata, compression, and integrity checksums stored alongside the actual image data","Automatic decryption of any BitLocker or FileVault volumes contained within the source disk drive","A guarantee that deleted files are permanently removed from the image to protect user privacy"], correct:1, explanation:"E01 adds metadata, compression, and CRC integrity checks. It does not auto-decrypt volumes, allow editing evidence, or purge deleted data." },
  { id:70335, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the AFF format in digital forensics?", options:["A proprietary Microsoft format used only for capturing volatile memory from a running system live","A file system, like NTFS, that investigators install on their analysis workstations directly here","An open, extensible forensic image format supporting compression and embedded case metadata too","A network protocol used to stream a suspect's disk over the wire during a remote acquisition job"], correct:2, explanation:"AFF (Advanced Forensic Format) is an open image format with compression and metadata. It is not a memory-only format, file system, or network protocol." },
  { id:70336, domain:3, level:3, question:"Which acquisition approach is preferred when a system cannot be powered down without losing data?", options:["Static acquisition, always performed after fully powering the machine off to ensure consistency now","Sparse acquisition of only the files the investigator believes are relevant to the current case file","Logical backup using the operating system's built-in scheduled backup utility running on a timer","Live acquisition, capturing volatile memory and disk data from the running system before shutdown"], correct:3, explanation:"Live acquisition captures volatile data from a running system. Static (dead) acquisition requires power-off, which would lose RAM and other volatile evidence." },
  { id:70337, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is file carving in digital forensics?", options:["Recovering files from raw data by recognizing header and footer signatures, ignoring file metadata","Splitting a large evidence image into smaller pieces so it fits on several backup media volumes","Permanently shredding sensitive files so that no forensic tool can ever reconstruct them again","Renaming recovered files according to their content so investigators can sort them quickly later overall"], correct:0, explanation:"Carving reconstructs files from raw data using signatures, independent of file system structures. It is not splitting, shredding, or renaming." },
  { id:70338, domain:3, level:3, question:"Which characteristic of a file does signature-based carving rely on most?", options:["The file's directory entry, which records its name and its exact location on the disk volume here","Known header and footer byte patterns, such as the JPEG FF D8 start and the FF D9 end markers","The file's NTFS security descriptor, listing the users who are permitted to read its contents now","The cluster size of the volume, which determines how the operating system stores the file on disk"], correct:1, explanation:"Signature carving keys on header/footer magic bytes like JPEG's FF D8 / FF D9. Directory entries and security descriptors are file-system metadata carving bypasses." },
  { id:70339, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why can file carving struggle to recover fragmented files correctly?", options:["Carving requires the original encryption key, which fragmented files split across several sectors","Carving only works on solid-state drives, where fragmentation never occurs in the first place at all","Carving assumes contiguous data, so fragments scattered across the disk may be missed or misjoined","Carving depends on the recycle bin, which fragmented files bypass when they are first deleted now"], correct:2, explanation:"Basic carving assumes contiguous storage, so fragmentation breaks reconstruction. Carving needs no key and is not limited to SSDs or the recycle bin." },
  { id:70340, domain:3, level:3, question:"When a file is deleted in the Windows Recycle Bin and then the bin is emptied, what usually happens?", options:["The data is securely erased with multiple overwrite passes the instant that the bin is emptied out","The file is moved to a hidden encrypted vault that only an administrator account may later open up","The MFT record is immediately shredded so no trace of the file name can ever be located again now","The clusters are marked free but the data often remains until overwritten, allowing later recovery"], correct:3, explanation:"Emptying the bin frees clusters but typically leaves data until overwritten, so recovery is often possible. No automatic multi-pass wipe occurs." },
  { id:70341, domain:3, level:1, question:"What do the MAC times of a file refer to in file system forensics?", options:["Modified, Accessed, and Created or Changed timestamps that record a file's key time-based events","The Media Access Control hardware address embedded inside the file's metadata header block here overall","Three checksums NTFS computes to detect silent corruption of a file's stored content bytes now","Memory, Address, and Cache values describing where the OS last buffered the file in system RAM"], correct:0, explanation:"MAC times are Modified, Accessed, and Created/Changed timestamps. They are unrelated to MAC hardware addresses, checksums, or memory buffers." },
  { id:70342, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does the last accessed timestamp on a file potentially indicate to an investigator?", options:["The exact moment the file's content was last modified and then written back to the disk volume","That the file was read or opened, though some systems disable updates for performance reasons","The time the file was first created on the volume, which never changes at all after that event","The number of distinct users who have ever opened the file since it was first written to disk"], correct:1, explanation:"The accessed time reflects reads/opens, though OSes (e.g., Windows with NtfsDisableLastAccessUpdate) may suppress it. It is not the modified or created time." },
  { id:70343, domain:3, level:1, question:"What are Windows Volume Shadow Copies useful for in a forensic investigation?", options:["They store a backup of every user's password so investigators can authenticate to the machine","They encrypt the entire volume so that only the system service can read protected files at runtime","They preserve earlier versions of files and the system, revealing data later changed or deleted","They permanently delete prior file versions to free disk space whenever the volume nears capacity"], correct:2, explanation:"Volume Shadow Copies retain prior file/system states, exposing changed or deleted data. They do not store passwords, encrypt volumes, or purge old versions." },
  { id:70344, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does BitLocker primarily protect on a Windows system?", options:["Individual files chosen by the user, leaving the rest of the volume entirely unencrypted on disk","Network traffic leaving the machine, by encrypting the packets before they reach the adapter card overall","The system clock and firmware settings, preventing tampering with the boot configuration data set","Full-volume encryption of the drive, protecting data at rest if the device is lost or stolen later"], correct:3, explanation:"BitLocker provides full-volume encryption for data at rest. EFS, not BitLocker, encrypts individual files; BitLocker does not encrypt network traffic." },
  { id:70345, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is commonly required to acquire data from a BitLocker-encrypted volume in plaintext?", options:["The recovery key, the user password, or a memory-captured key, since the data is otherwise unreadable","Simply removing the drive and connecting it to a Linux machine, which ignores all encryption entirely","A second copy of the same Windows installation media to reinstall over the locked volume from scratch","Physically degaussing the drive first, which conveniently strips the encryption layer away from data"], correct:0, explanation:"Decryption needs the recovery key, password, or extracted key. Moving the drive to Linux still encounters encryption, and degaussing destroys data." },
  { id:70346, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is FileVault on macOS?", options:["A cloud backup service that uploads encrypted copies of the user's documents automatically each day","Apple's full-disk encryption feature that protects the startup volume's data while it is at rest","A sandbox that isolates downloaded applications from the rest of the operating system at all times","A firmware password that merely blocks booting from external media on Apple Mac hardware devices"], correct:1, explanation:"FileVault is Apple's full-disk encryption. It is not a cloud backup, app sandbox, or the separate firmware password feature." },
  { id:70347, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is timestomping as an anti-forensic technique?", options:["Flooding the system clock with requests so the operating system records no times at all anymore","Encrypting the file system journal so that the sequence of changes cannot be reconstructed later","Deliberately altering a file's timestamps to mislead investigators about when events occurred","Physically overwriting the disk's timing tracks so platters can no longer spin at their full speed"], correct:2, explanation:"Timestomping alters file timestamps to deceive investigators. It is not a clock-flooding, journal-encryption, or physical-platter technique." },
  { id:70348, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which anti-forensic method hides data inside the slack space of allocated clusters?", options:["Steganography, which conceals a message only inside the visible pixels of standard image files here","Disk degaussing, which uses a strong magnetic field to erase the entire drive all at once quickly","Log scrubbing, which removes incriminating entries from the system's event log files after access","Slack space data hiding, which places information in the unused tail of a file's last cluster area"], correct:3, explanation:"Hiding data in cluster slack uses unused tail space. Steganography hides in media content, degaussing erases, and log scrubbing edits logs, all different." },
  { id:70349, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does secure deletion (wiping) software aim to achieve?", options:["Overwriting data so that it cannot be recovered, unlike a normal delete that only frees clusters","Compressing the deleted files into an archive that can later be restored on demand by the user now","Moving the files into the operating system's recycle bin where they are then kept indefinitely too","Renaming the files with random characters while leaving their original content fully intact still"], correct:0, explanation:"Wiping overwrites data to prevent recovery, unlike normal deletion that just frees clusters. It does not archive, recycle, or merely rename files." },
  { id:70350, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is The Sleuth Kit in digital forensics?", options:["A proprietary hardware write blocker sold for connecting suspect drives to a workstation port","An open-source library and command-line tools for analyzing disk images and the file systems","A cloud platform that stores chain-of-custody records for law enforcement evidence rooms today","A network sniffer that captures the packets traversing a suspect's local area network segment"], correct:1, explanation:"TSK is an open-source toolkit for disk image and file system analysis. It is not hardware, a cloud custody system, or a packet sniffer." },
  { id:70351, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is Autopsy in the context of forensic investigations?", options:["A live memory acquisition agent installed on suspect machines to dump volatile RAM remotely now","A write-blocking bridge that sits between the suspect disk and the examiner's computer port here","A graphical front end to The Sleuth Kit used to analyze disk images and recover the artifacts","A disk-wiping utility certified to overwrite drives to meet government sanitization standards too"], correct:2, explanation:"Autopsy is a GUI built on TSK for image analysis. It is not a RAM agent, write blocker, or wiping tool." },
  { id:70352, domain:3, level:2, question:"For what is the FTK Imager tool commonly used?", options:["Permanently shredding evidence drives once a case has been fully closed by the presiding court","Encrypting the examiner's report files so that opposing counsel cannot read the conclusions later","Generating fake timestamps on files to test how robust an investigation procedure really is now","Creating forensic disk images and previewing their contents without altering the source media"], correct:3, explanation:"FTK Imager creates and previews forensic images without altering the source. It is not a shredder, report encryptor, or timestamp faker." },
  { id:70353, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does EnCase provide to forensic examiners?", options:["A commercial suite for acquiring, analyzing, and reporting on digital evidence from many sources","Only a hardware write blocker with no accompanying software for analyzing the captured data later","A free open-source kernel module that mounts encrypted volumes without any decryption key at all","A purely network-based intrusion prevention system that blocks attacks in real time at the edge"], correct:0, explanation:"EnCase is a commercial acquisition, analysis, and reporting suite. It is software, not just a write blocker, and not an IPS or key-bypass module." },
  { id:70354, domain:3, level:3, question:"How many bytes are in a traditional disk sector before the advent of Advanced Format drives?", options:["1024 bytes, double the modern cluster size that most file systems prefer to allocate to files today","512 bytes, the classic sector size used by hard drives for many decades before 4K sectors arrived","256 bytes, half of the value that newer Advanced Format drives later standardized upon as default","4096 bytes, which only became the standard sector size on much older legacy disk hardware models"], correct:1, explanation:"Classic sectors are 512 bytes; Advanced Format later introduced 4096-byte sectors. The 4K value is the newer standard, not the legacy one." },
  { id:70355, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is unallocated space on a forensic image?", options:["The region reserved exclusively for the operating system's own protected internal system files overall","Space that the file system has permanently zeroed and that can never contain recoverable data","Disk areas not currently assigned to any file, which may still hold recoverable deleted data here","The portion of RAM that the operating system has not yet handed out to any running process"], correct:2, explanation:"Unallocated space holds no current file but may retain deleted data. It is not zeroed automatically nor a RAM region." },
  { id:70356, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the difference between physical and logical acquisition of a storage device?", options:["Physical copies only the live files, while logical copies the entire raw contents bit for bit","Physical works only on SSDs, while logical works exclusively on the spinning magnetic disks","Physical requires no write blocker, while logical always demands a hardware write blocker too","Physical copies every bit of the device, while logical copies only the live files and folders"], correct:3, explanation:"Physical acquisition captures every bit including slack/unallocated; logical captures only live files. The roles are not reversed, and neither is media-specific." },
  { id:70357, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the purpose of the $MFT mirror file ($MFTMirr) in NTFS?", options:["It stores a backup of the first records of the MFT so the volume can recover if the MFT is damaged","It keeps a second copy of every file's content for redundancy against any bad sectors on the disk","It records a log of all of the user logons to the machine for later auditing by administrators now","It mirrors the BitLocker recovery keys so the volume can be unlocked after a corruption event too"], correct:0, explanation:"$MFTMirr backs up critical MFT records for recovery. It does not duplicate all file content, log logons, or store BitLocker keys." },
  { id:70358, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does the term data run describe in NTFS?", options:["A scheduled background task that defragments files to make their clusters contiguous over time now","A mapping of an attribute's non-resident data to the runs of clusters where it is stored on disk","The continuous stream of timestamps NTFS updates each and every time a file is opened by a user","A sequence of failed read attempts the drive records before it marks a given sector as defective"], correct:1, explanation:"A data run maps non-resident attribute data to its cluster runs. It is not a defrag task, timestamp stream, or read-error log." },
  { id:70359, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why are slack space and unallocated space important sources of forensic evidence?", options:["They always store the most recent and most complete version of every active file on the disk volume","They are the only places where a file's current security permissions are recorded by NTFS metadata","They can contain remnants of deleted files and earlier data that the user believes was fully erased","They hold the encryption keys that are used to protect the rest of the data stored on the volume"], correct:2, explanation:"Slack and unallocated areas often retain deleted/old data. They do not hold current file versions, permissions, or encryption keys." },
  { id:70360, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is a forensic hash set such as the NSRL used for?", options:["Encrypting evidence images so that only the investigators holding the set can open them up later","Permanently deleting known illegal files from a suspect drive during the disk imaging process now","Storing the timestamps of every operating system file for later chronological reconstruction work","Identifying known files by hash so investigators can filter out common, irrelevant system files"], correct:3, explanation:"Hash sets like the NSRL identify known files to filter noise (or flag known-bad). They do not encrypt images, delete files, or store timestamps." },
  { id:70361, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the role of a chain of custody document in storage forensics?", options:["It records who handled the evidence, when, and why, preserving its integrity and admissibility","It lists the cluster chains of every recovered file so that they can be reassembled correctly later","It encrypts the evidence drive so that unauthorized personnel cannot access the contents at all now","It indexes the file system metadata to accelerate keyword searches across the whole disk image"], correct:0, explanation:"Chain of custody documents handling to preserve admissibility. It is not a cluster map, encryption, or search index despite the similar-sounding name." },
  { id:70362, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the significance of the JPEG file signature FF D8 FF in carving?", options:["It is the footer that always marks the very end of a JPEG file on the physical storage medium","It is the header magic number carvers use to locate the start of a JPEG image in the raw data","It is the encryption marker showing the image has been protected with a password by the user","It is the checksum the camera writes so the file system can verify the photo's integrity later"], correct:1, explanation:"FF D8 FF is the JPEG header signature used to find image starts. The JPEG footer is FF D9, and the bytes are not an encryption or checksum marker." },
  { id:70363, domain:3, level:1, question:"Which Windows artifact records details of recently executed programs and is useful in forensics?", options:["The page file, which exclusively stores a list of every program a user has ever installed on disk","The recycle bin, which logs each executable launch along with the precise time of the given action","Prefetch files, which the system creates to speed launches and which reveal program execution","The MBR, which keeps a chronological history of all applications run since the disk was formatted"], correct:2, explanation:"Prefetch files evidence program execution. The page file, recycle bin, and MBR do not catalog program runs in that way." },
  { id:70364, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does write blocking accomplish that simply mounting a disk read-only does not guarantee?", options:["Automatic encryption of the suspect disk so that its data cannot be altered after the acquisition","Faster imaging speeds because the blocker caches the entire disk in memory before copying it across","Conversion of the suspect file system into a universal format that every analysis tool can read","Hardware-level prevention of writes, removing reliance on the OS to honor a read-only setting flag"], correct:3, explanation:"A hardware write blocker enforces no-write at the bus level, not trusting OS read-only flags. It does not encrypt, cache, or convert file systems." },
  { id:70365, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the typical default cluster size impact on slack space?", options:["Larger clusters create more slack per file, since each file rounds up to a whole cluster boundary","Larger clusters eliminate slack entirely because files are stored without any wasted tail space now","Cluster size has no effect on slack, which depends solely on the physical sector size of the disk","Smaller clusters create more slack because the file system must track many more allocation units"], correct:0, explanation:"Bigger clusters mean more wasted tail space (slack) per file. Slack does not vanish with large clusters, and smaller clusters reduce per-file slack." },
  { id:70366, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the GUID Partition Table store for each partition?", options:["The full directory listing of every file contained inside that partition for quick indexing later","A unique GUID, the partition type, and the starting and ending LBAs that bound the partition area","A complete copy of the partition's boot loader and the operating system kernel for redundancy too","The encryption key needed to unlock the partition whenever the system boots up directly from it"], correct:1, explanation:"Each GPT entry holds a unique GUID, type, and start/end LBAs. It does not store file listings, the kernel, or encryption keys." },
  { id:70367, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does imaging to a sparse format help conserve during acquisition?", options:["Time spent hashing, by skipping the integrity verification of the acquired image entirely each run","The original drive's lifespan, by reducing the number of reads performed on the source media too","Storage space, by not writing long runs of zeroed or empty sectors to the output image file at all","Encryption overhead, by storing the image in plaintext rather than inside an encrypted container"], correct:2, explanation:"Sparse images skip storing empty/zero runs, saving space. They do not skip hashing, reduce source reads, or change encryption." },
  { id:70368, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the role of the volume boot record in a partition?", options:["It stores the partition table for the whole disk, mapping out where each partition begins on disk","It holds the master file table for an NTFS partition along with every file's actual data content","It records the system's BIOS settings so they survive even when the CMOS battery finally dies","It contains boot code and parameters for that specific partition's file system to begin loading"], correct:3, explanation:"The VBR holds partition-specific boot code and file-system parameters. The disk-wide partition table is in the MBR, and the MFT is separate." },
  { id:70369, domain:3, level:2, question:"When examining an SSD, why might the TRIM command frustrate recovery of deleted files?", options:["TRIM tells the drive to erase blocks of deleted files in the background, thereby removing the data","TRIM encrypts every deleted file with a key that is then immediately discarded by the drive itself","TRIM relocates the deleted files into the host protected area where examiners cannot reach them","TRIM compresses deleted files so tightly that file carving tools can no longer recognize them"], correct:0, explanation:"TRIM causes the SSD to purge deleted blocks, defeating recovery. It does not encrypt, relocate to HPA, or compress deleted data." },
  { id:70370, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the term bad sector reallocation mean on a hard drive?", options:["The operating system permanently deletes any file that happens to touch a failing disk sector now","The drive transparently maps a failing sector to a spare one, possibly leaving old data orphaned","The file system moves the entire partition to a different disk when sectors begin to fail over time","The BIOS reformats the drive automatically whenever the number of bad sectors grows too large"], correct:1, explanation:"Reallocation remaps a bad sector to a spare, sometimes stranding old data (a G-list/P-list concept). It is not file deletion, partition moving, or auto-reformat." },
  { id:70371, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which statement about the NTFS $Bitmap metadata file is correct?", options:["It contains a thumbnail bitmap image preview of every single picture file stored on the volume too","It records the screen resolution and color depth the system used at the time of each user logon","It tracks which clusters on the volume are allocated and which are free for new data to be stored","It stores the encrypted bitmap of fingerprint data for users who log in using their biometrics"], correct:2, explanation:"$Bitmap maps allocated versus free clusters. It is unrelated to image thumbnails, display settings, or biometric data." },
  { id:70372, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the forensic value of examining the Windows registry hives on an image?", options:["They contain a full bit-for-bit copy of every deleted file that ever existed on the system disk","They hold the cluster allocation table that the NTFS file system uses to place new files on disk overall","They record the spinning speed and the temperature history of the physical hard disk drive unit","They store configuration, user activity, installed software, and connected device information too"], correct:3, explanation:"Registry hives reveal configuration, user activity, software, and device history. They are not a deleted-file store, allocation table, or drive telemetry log." },
  { id:70373, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why is hashing the source drive before and after imaging considered best practice?", options:["Matching hashes prove the imaging process did not alter the original evidence drive at all here","Differing hashes are required to prove that the examiner compressed the resulting image properly","Hashing twice doubles the encryption strength that is applied to the resulting forensic image file","Re-hashing automatically repairs any sectors that became corrupted during the entire copy process"], correct:0, explanation:"Matching before/after hashes show the original was unaltered. Hashing does not compress, encrypt, or repair data." },
  { id:70374, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the main forensic concern when a suspect machine is found powered on?", options:["The hard drive will instantly wipe itself the very moment an investigator unplugs the power cable","Volatile data in RAM, such as running processes and encryption keys, is lost once power is removed","The BIOS password changes automatically every time the machine is left running for far too long now","The file system converts from NTFS to FAT32 whenever the system stays powered for many hours"], correct:1, explanation:"A live machine holds volatile RAM evidence (keys, processes) lost on shutdown. Drives do not auto-wipe, and file systems do not self-convert." },
  { id:70375, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is RAM slack specifically?", options:["The portion of system memory reserved permanently for the operating system kernel processes here","A region of the page file dedicated to caching recently closed application windows for fast reuse","The padding the OS adds to fill the last sector of a file, sometimes containing memory remnants","The unused capacity of a RAM module that the memory controller never maps into address space now"], correct:2, explanation:"RAM slack is OS padding in a file's last sector that may carry memory contents. It is not reserved kernel memory or unmapped RAM." },
  { id:70376, domain:3, level:3, question:"What distinguishes drive slack from RAM slack within file slack?", options:["Drive slack is the encrypted portion of a file, while RAM slack is the plaintext portion of it now","Drive slack exists only on SSDs, whereas RAM slack appears solely on the spinning magnetic disks","Drive slack stores the file's permissions, while RAM slack stores the file's modification times","Drive slack is the remaining clusters' sectors after RAM slack, often holding prior deleted data"], correct:3, explanation:"Drive slack is the leftover sectors after RAM slack and can hold old data. The other options misdefine these two components of file slack." },
  { id:70377, domain:3, level:3, question:"What information does an NTFS directory index ($I30) hold?", options:["B-tree index entries listing the files within a folder, including their names and some metadata","The complete content of every file in the folder so the directory can serve them out directly now","A backup of the volume boot record kept in case the original at the partition start ever fails","The list of bad clusters on the volume that NTFS avoids when allocating space for any new files"], correct:0, explanation:"$I30 is the B-tree index of a directory's entries. It does not store file content, the VBR backup, or the bad-cluster list ($BadClus)." },
  { id:70378, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why are deleted entries in an NTFS $I30 index valuable to investigators?", options:["They contain the full decrypted content of every file that was previously deleted from the disk now","They can reveal names of files once in a folder even after those files have been removed from disk","They list the IP addresses of every remote computer that ever connected to the machine over time","They store the only copy of the user's login password in a recoverable plaintext form on the disk"], correct:1, explanation:"Slack within $I30 can retain deleted file names. It does not hold file content, network logs, or passwords." },
  { id:70379, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the function of the $BadClus metadata file in NTFS?", options:["It stores a backup copy of the master boot record for the entire physical disk drive in question","It logs every cluster that has ever been written to since the volume was first formatted by a user","It tracks clusters marked defective so the file system avoids allocating any data to them later","It holds the directory tree for the volume's root so the OS can mount the partition at boot time"], correct:2, explanation:"$BadClus records defective clusters to avoid them. It is not an MBR backup, a write log, or the root directory." },
  { id:70380, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does logical block addressing replace from older disk addressing?", options:["The file allocation table, by mapping each file directly to a numbered cluster on the disk volume","The master boot record, by storing the partition boundaries inside the drive firmware itself now","The inode table, by giving each Linux file a globally unique numeric identifier on the disk volume","The cylinder-head-sector scheme, by numbering every sector with a single linear value across disk"], correct:3, explanation:"LBA replaced CHS addressing with linear sector numbers. It is not a replacement for the FAT, MBR, or inode table." },
  { id:70381, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the primary risk of booting a suspect drive in its original machine?", options:["The boot process writes to the drive, altering timestamps and potentially destroying the evidence","The drive will refuse to spin up unless it is connected through a hardware write blocker first now","The BIOS will permanently encrypt the drive the moment the operating system finishes loading up","The file system will silently convert all deleted files into unrecoverable random noise data now"], correct:0, explanation:"Booting writes to the disk and alters evidence. Drives do not require a blocker to spin, and booting does not auto-encrypt or scramble data." },
  { id:70382, domain:3, level:1, question:"Which tool component of The Sleuth Kit lists files and directories in a disk image?", options:["dd, which simply copies raw bytes from one device or file to another without any parsing at all","fls, which displays file and directory names, including some deleted entries, from a disk image","netstat, which shows the active network connections on a currently running live operating system","regedit, which opens and edits the Windows registry hives on a live running operating system here"], correct:1, explanation:"fls lists files/directories (including deleted) from an image. dd copies bytes, and netstat/regedit are unrelated OS utilities." },
  { id:70383, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does the TSK tool icat do?", options:["Catalogs every installed network interface card present in the suspect computer system at the time","Encrypts a forensic image so that it can be transmitted securely to a remote analysis lab elsewhere","Outputs the contents of a file specified by its inode or MFT entry number from a given disk image","Calculates the integrity hash of an entire physical disk before the imaging process even begins"], correct:2, explanation:"icat extracts file content by inode/MFT number. It is not a NIC catalog, an encryptor, or a hashing tool." },
  { id:70384, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the purpose of computing a hash of each file during analysis, not just the whole image?", options:["To compress each file individually so the overall evidence image takes far less storage to keep","To encrypt each file so that investigators holding the wrong credentials cannot read the content","To permanently remove duplicate files from the evidence so that the case folder stays smaller now","To identify known files, detect duplicates, and flag files altered from their expected versions"], correct:3, explanation:"Per-file hashing supports known-file matching, dedup detection, and tamper checks. It does not compress, encrypt, or delete files." },
  { id:70385, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is a forensic wipe of a target drive before imaging onto it?", options:["Overwriting the destination media so no residual data contaminates the newly created forensic image","Encrypting the destination drive so the captured evidence is protected against any later theft loss","Compressing the destination drive's free space to make room for the much larger evidence image","Formatting the source suspect drive so that the examiner can mount it with their own tools later"], correct:0, explanation:"Wiping the destination prevents cross-contamination of evidence. It targets the destination, not the source, and is not encryption or compression." },
  { id:70386, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the acronym AFF4 represent as an evolution of AFF?", options:["A proprietary cloud service used only by federal agencies to archive their completed case files","A modern open forensic format supporting layered, multi-volume, and large-scale evidence storage","A file system designed to replace NTFS on forensic workstations for much faster analysis speeds","A network streaming protocol that transfers disk images between two examiners in real time today"], correct:1, explanation:"AFF4 is a modern open forensic image format. It is not a cloud service, file system, or streaming protocol." },
  { id:70387, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which factor most determines whether a deleted file can be recovered?", options:["Whether the file's name began with a vowel or a consonant when it was first created on the disk","Whether the drive is mounted as the C: volume or instead as a secondary lettered drive on the system","Whether its clusters have been overwritten by new data since the file was originally deleted","Whether the file was larger or smaller than the system's total amount of installed physical memory"], correct:2, explanation:"Recovery hinges on whether the data clusters were overwritten. Filename letters, drive letter, and file-versus-RAM size are irrelevant." },
  { id:70388, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the role of the $UsnJrnl USN journal in NTFS forensics?", options:["It stores the only copy of each user's password hash for the local Windows accounts present here","It keeps a full backup of deleted files so that they can always be restored from the journal later","It contains the BitLocker recovery passwords for every encrypted volume found on the machine","It records a change log of files and directories, useful for reconstructing the recent activity"], correct:3, explanation:"$UsnJrnl logs file/directory changes for activity reconstruction. It is not a password store, deleted-file backup, or BitLocker key vault." },
  { id:70389, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why might an investigator examine the pagefile.sys or hiberfil.sys files?", options:["They can contain fragments of memory, including passwords, keys, or data from the running programs","They store the master file table that NTFS relies upon to locate every file present on the volume","They hold the disk's partition table, mapping where each partition starts and ends on the disk now","They contain the firmware of the hard drive, which controls how sectors are physically read back"], correct:0, explanation:"Page and hibernation files capture memory contents that may include keys/data. They are not the MFT, partition table, or drive firmware." },
  { id:70390, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does data carving by file structure add beyond simple header and footer carving?", options:["It requires the original encryption key to be supplied before any single file can be reconstructed","It uses internal file format knowledge to validate and reassemble fragmented files more accurately","It only recovers files whose names are still present within the file system directory entries now","It works exclusively on optical media such as CDs and DVDs rather than on the magnetic disks"], correct:1, explanation:"Structure-based carving uses format internals to handle fragmentation and validation. It needs no key, ignores directory entries by design, and is not optical-only." },
  { id:70391, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the consequence of defragmentation for deleted-file recovery?", options:["It permanently encrypts all of the deleted files so that no recovery tool can ever read them again","It moves the deleted files into the recycle bin where they then remain safely recoverable forever","It can overwrite previously deleted data as it relocates active files into contiguous clusters","It has no effect at all on deleted data because it only ever touches the disk's partition table"], correct:2, explanation:"Defrag relocates active files, potentially overwriting deleted data. It does not encrypt deleted files, restore them, or limit itself to the partition table." },
  { id:70392, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which structure in ext4 improves on ext3's block mapping for large files?", options:["Alternate data streams, borrowed from NTFS to attach hidden data to each Linux file present here","A file allocation table, adopted from FAT to chain clusters together across the whole disk volume","The host protected area, used to reserve hidden capacity for very large files placed on the disk","Extents, which describe ranges of contiguous blocks instead of mapping each block individually"], correct:3, explanation:"ext4 uses extents for efficient contiguous-range mapping. ADS, FAT, and HPA are unrelated concepts from other systems." },
  { id:70393, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of journaling in a file system from a forensic standpoint?", options:["It records pending changes, leaving a trail that can reveal recent file system activity to analysts","It encrypts the volume so that only authorized users can mount and read the file system data later overall","It compresses files automatically to reduce the overall storage footprint of the entire volume now","It hides deleted files from investigators by removing all trace of them from the disk immediately"], correct:0, explanation:"Journals log pending metadata changes, which can reveal recent activity. Journaling is not encryption, compression, or evidence hiding." },
  { id:70394, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is a key forensic difference between a quick format and a full format of a volume?", options:["A quick format overwrites every sector with zeros, while a full format leaves all data fully intact","A quick format only resets file system structures, leaving most of the old data recoverable on disk","A quick format encrypts the volume, while a full format simply changes the assigned drive letter","A quick format physically degausses the platters, while a full format only edits the metadata"], correct:1, explanation:"Quick format resets structures but leaves data recoverable; full format may overwrite or check sectors. The other options invert or misstate this." },
  { id:70395, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is the order of volatility important during evidence collection?", options:["The least volatile data such as archived backups must always be seized before anything else first overall","Volatility determines which encryption algorithm the examiner should apply to the seized evidence","The most volatile data, like RAM and network state, must be collected before it disappears entirely","The order only matters for optical media, which degrades faster than any other storage type known"], correct:2, explanation:"Order of volatility says collect the most volatile data (RAM, network) first. It is not about encryption choice or optical media." },
  { id:70396, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does remanence refer to in storage forensics?", options:["The magnetic field strength a degausser must exceed to render a hard drive fully unreadable later","The amount of free space remaining on a volume after the operating system has been installed now","The time a solid-state drive can retain data without power before the stored charge leaks away","Residual data that persists on media even after deletion or an attempted erasure of the content"], correct:3, explanation:"Remanence is residual data persisting after erasure attempts. It is not degausser field strength, free space, or SSD charge retention specifically." },
  { id:70397, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the forensic relevance of the $Recycle.Bin folder structure on NTFS?", options:["It stores deleted files alongside $I metadata recording the original path, size, and deletion time","It contains the master boot record and the partition table for the disk holding the recycle bin","It keeps a full copy of the system registry so deleted configuration can always be restored later overall","It holds the encryption keys that protect every other folder that is stored on the same volume"], correct:0, explanation:"The $Recycle.Bin keeps deleted files with $I metadata (path, size, delete time). It is not the MBR, a registry copy, or a key store." },
  { id:70398, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does write amplification on SSDs refer to that complicates forensics?", options:["The drive duplicates every written file to a backup region so deleted data is always preserved","The controller rewrites more data than the host sent, moving and erasing blocks unpredictably","The host operating system writes evidence logs that grow larger than the data being captured","The imaging tool writes the captured image multiple times to verify its integrity on the media"], correct:1, explanation:"Write amplification means the SSD controller moves/erases more than requested, scrambling block locations. It is not deliberate backup or repeated image writing." },
  { id:70399, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is the SSD controller's internal mapping the Flash Translation Layer a forensic challenge?", options:["The Flash Translation Layer encrypts every file with a key the host can never obtain or recover","The Flash Translation Layer streams all writes to a remote server before storing them locally too overall","The Flash Translation Layer hides the true physical location of data from the host system entirely","The Flash Translation Layer prevents the drive from ever reporting its true total capacity to OS"], correct:2, explanation:"The FTL abstracts physical block locations from the host, hindering direct analysis. It is not an encryption, streaming, or capacity-hiding mechanism." },
  { id:70400, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does a sparse file mean in NTFS?", options:["A file that is split into many tiny fragments scattered randomly across the entire volume surface","A file that exists in the MFT but whose name has been removed from its parent directory entirely","A file stored entirely within the volume slack space rather than in normally allocated clusters","A file whose large empty regions are not allocated on disk, recorded only as the zero data ranges"], correct:3, explanation:"A sparse file leaves empty regions unallocated, stored as zero ranges. It is not defined by fragmentation, orphaning, or slack-space storage." },
  { id:70401, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the significance of an orphaned file in NTFS forensics?", options:["Its MFT record exists but its parent directory link is lost, so tools list it separately to user","Its content has been fully encrypted and the decryption key has been permanently deleted already","Its data resides only in RAM and has never once been written to the physical disk at any time now","Its timestamps are all set to zero because the file was created before the system clock had begun"], correct:0, explanation:"An orphaned file has an MFT record but no valid parent link. It is not defined by encryption, RAM-only residence, or zero timestamps." },
  { id:70402, domain:3, level:1, question:"Which is true about FAT12, used historically on floppy disks?", options:["It uses 64-bit cluster entries, making it suitable for even the largest of modern storage arrays","It uses 12-bit cluster entries, limiting it to a small number of clusters and very tiny volumes","It includes a full transactional journal identical to the one that the NTFS file system provides","It encrypts every file by default using a key that is derived from the floppy disk serial number"], correct:1, explanation:"FAT12 uses 12-bit entries, suiting tiny volumes. It is not 64-bit, journaled, or encrypted by default." },
  { id:70403, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does mounting an image read-only during analysis prevent?", options:["The image from being compressed any further to save space on the examiner's workstation storage","The operating system from ever displaying the names of any files contained within the disk image","Accidental modification of the evidence image while the files inside are examined by the analyst","The hash of the image from being calculated, which would otherwise alter its underlying contents"], correct:2, explanation:"Read-only mounting prevents accidental changes to evidence. It does not affect compression, file listing, or hashing of the image." },
  { id:70404, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why might investigators look at thumbnail caches such as thumbs.db or thumbcache?", options:["They store the full-resolution master copy of every photo ever opened on the computer over time","They contain the cluster allocation map that the file system uses to place any new files on disk","They hold the user's login password as a thumbnail-sized encrypted bitmap stored on the disk now","They can retain small previews of images even after the original picture files have been deleted"], correct:3, explanation:"Thumbnail caches can retain previews of deleted images. They do not store full-res masters, allocation maps, or passwords." },
  { id:70405, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the term physical disk geometry (CHS) describe?", options:["The cylinders, heads, and sectors used to address data on the traditional spinning hard drives","The shape and dimensions of the SSD circuit board including its NAND chip placement layout too","The logical partition boundaries recorded inside the GUID partition table at the disk's very start","The cluster size and file allocation table layout chosen when a volume is first formatted by user"], correct:0, explanation:"CHS geometry is cylinders, heads, sectors of spinning disks. It is not SSD board layout, GPT boundaries, or cluster/FAT layout." },
  { id:70406, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the benefit of acquiring volatile memory before imaging the disk?", options:["Imaging RAM first automatically decrypts every encrypted volume on the attached hard disk drive","RAM may contain encryption keys, passwords, and active data lost the very moment power is cut off","Memory acquisition permanently wipes the disk, which conveniently simplifies the later imaging","RAM capture is the only way to obtain the disk's partition table for any later reconstruction work"], correct:1, explanation:"RAM holds volatile keys/passwords lost on power-off, so capture it first. It does not auto-decrypt volumes, wipe disks, or hold the partition table." },
  { id:70407, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does a known good baseline hash database help an investigator do?", options:["Encrypt the entire evidence image using a key that is derived from the baseline hash values here","Permanently delete every file whose hash matches a known good operating system file on the disk","Quickly exclude unmodified operating system files so the attention focuses on the unusual files","Recover deleted files by matching their content fragments against the stored baseline hash entries"], correct:2, explanation:"A known-good hash set filters out standard files to highlight anomalies. It does not encrypt, delete, or carve files." },
  { id:70408, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is live forensics best suited to capture that dead-box forensics cannot?", options:["The complete unallocated space of the disk, which only appears when the system is fully powered off","The drive's firmware revision, which can only be read while the machine is completely shut down now","The partition table, which is hidden by the operating system whenever the machine is running live","Running processes, open network connections, and decrypted data present only in the system memory"], correct:3, explanation:"Live forensics captures volatile state (processes, connections, in-memory plaintext). Unallocated space and partition tables are accessible in dead-box analysis." },
  { id:70409, domain:3, level:2, question:"What role does the EFI System Partition play on a UEFI/GPT disk?", options:["It holds boot loaders and drivers the UEFI firmware reads to start the operating system at boot","It stores all of the user documents in an encrypted container that only the firmware can unlock","It contains the master file table for the main NTFS partition on the same physical disk drive too","It keeps a continuous log of every keystroke entered since the machine was first set up by user"], correct:0, explanation:"The ESP stores boot loaders/drivers for UEFI. It is not a user-data vault, the MFT, or a keystroke log." },
  { id:70410, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the main reason to validate a forensic tool before relying on its output in court?", options:["To ensure the tool encrypts its results so that opposing experts cannot review any of the findings","To establish that the tool reliably produces accurate, reproducible results on the known data sets","To confirm the tool can permanently delete the suspect's data after the analysis is fully complete","To guarantee the tool runs faster than any competing product on the examiner's chosen hardware"], correct:1, explanation:"Tool validation establishes accuracy and reproducibility for admissibility. It is not about encryption, deletion, or raw speed." },
  { id:70411, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does file signature analysis versus extension detect?", options:["Files that have been compressed to a smaller size than their original content normally allowed for","Files the user has marked as hidden so they do not appear in any normal directory listing on disk","Files whose true type, shown by the header bytes, differs from their misleading file extension","Files that exceed the maximum size the file system is able to address on the current disk volume"], correct:2, explanation:"Signature analysis spots mismatches between header bytes and the extension (e.g., renamed files). It does not detect compression, hidden flags, or size limits." },
  { id:70412, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which is a recognized standard for sanitizing media, relevant to anti-forensics awareness?", options:["RFC 1918, which reserves private IP address ranges for use inside the local networks only here overall","IEEE 802.11, which specifies how wireless local area networks transmit their data over the air","ISO 9660, which defines the file system layout used on standard read-only CD-ROM disc media","NIST SP 800-88, which defines the clear, purge, and destroy methods used for media sanitization"], correct:3, explanation:"NIST SP 800-88 governs media sanitization. RFC 1918, IEEE 802.11, and ISO 9660 concern IP addressing, Wi-Fi, and CD file systems respectively." },
  { id:70413, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does clearing a drive mean under NIST sanitization terminology?", options:["Overwriting the user-addressable storage so data cannot be recovered with the standard tools","Physically shredding the platters so that no fragment larger than a few millimeters then remains","Encrypting the drive and then discarding the key while leaving all of the ciphertext fully intact","Removing the partition table only, which leaves every file's underlying data completely untouched"], correct:0, explanation:"Clearing overwrites user-addressable space against standard recovery. Shredding is 'destroy', and crypto-erase/partition removal are different methods." },
  { id:70414, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is documenting the system date and time during seizure important?", options:["The system clock encrypts the file system, so its value is needed to unlock the volume later on too","A skewed system clock affects interpretation of every timestamp found on the seized evidence drive","The clock value is the only way to compute the cryptographic hash of the seized disk image at all","Recording the time is required because the drive deletes data once its clock reaches midnight hour"], correct:1, explanation:"A wrong clock skews timestamp interpretation, so it must be noted. The clock does not encrypt, hash, or trigger deletion." },
  { id:70415, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the forensic implication of full-disk encryption being active at seizure?", options:["The drive can always be decrypted instantly by removing it and attaching it to almost any reader","The encryption automatically disables itself the moment the machine is disconnected from its power","The drive should ideally be imaged while powered and unlocked, or the key must somehow be obtained","The encrypted data is impossible to image at all, so the drive should simply be discarded entirely"], correct:2, explanation:"With FDE active, capture while unlocked or obtain the key. The drive is not trivially decryptable, does not auto-disable, and can still be imaged (as ciphertext)." },
  { id:70416, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does cross-drive analysis help investigators discover?", options:["The spinning speed of every drive in a forensic lab compared against the manufacturer's own spec overall","Whether a single drive has more bad sectors than another otherwise identical drive model present","The total electrical power consumed by all the drives examined during a particular investigation","Connections between multiple drives or devices, such as shared files, accounts, or saved contacts"], correct:3, explanation:"Cross-drive analysis correlates artifacts across multiple devices. It is not about drive speed, bad-sector counts, or power use." },
  { id:70417, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the purpose of a working copy in forensic examination?", options:["Analysts examine a duplicate so the original evidence image remains pristine and entirely unaltered","The working copy is the only version that actually contains the deleted files needing recovery now overall","A working copy must always be encrypted before the original disk image can even be created at all","The working copy stores the chain of custody log that the original disk image is unable to hold"], correct:0, explanation:"Work is done on a copy to keep the original pristine. The copy is not uniquely able to hold deleted files, custody logs, or a prerequisite for imaging." },
  { id:70418, domain:3, level:3, question:"How does NTFS compression affect file carving and analysis?", options:["Compressed files are automatically excluded from the MFT, so they never appear to any tools used","Compressed runs must be decompressed using NTFS logic, so naive carving may yield only garbage","Compression encrypts the file content, requiring the user's password before any analysis can begin","Compressed files cannot be deleted, so they are always trivially recovered fully intact later on"], correct:1, explanation:"Carving compressed NTFS data without applying decompression yields garbage. Compression is not exclusion from the MFT, encryption, or undeletable storage." },
  { id:70419, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the value of examining link files (.lnk shortcuts) in Windows forensics?", options:["They contain a full copy of the file they point to, so the original can always be recovered later","They store the user's password so the system can reopen protected files without any later prompt","They embed the target path, timestamps, and volume info, evidencing access to specific files","They hold the master file table records for every file located in the same folder as the link too"], correct:2, explanation:"LNK files record target paths, timestamps, and volume serials, evidencing file access. They do not embed the target's content, passwords, or the MFT." },
  { id:70420, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does data acquisition verification specifically require?", options:["Confirming the suspect drive has been physically destroyed right after the image has been captured","Confirming the analysis workstation has more storage than the size of the captured image at hand","Confirming the investigator has memorized the partition table before beginning any of the analysis","Confirming the image's hash matches the source so the copy is proven complete and fully accurate"], correct:3, explanation:"Verification confirms the image hash matches the source. It is not about destroying the source, workstation capacity, or memorization." },
  { id:70421, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why might unallocated space contain old MFT records in NTFS?", options:["MFT records of deleted files may persist until reused, allowing the reconstruction of past files","NTFS always copies every active MFT record into the unallocated space for redundancy purposes too","Unallocated space is where NTFS exclusively stores the live MFT while the volume is fully mounted","MFT records are written to the unallocated space only after the user empties the recycle bin once"], correct:0, explanation:"Deleted-file MFT records can linger until reused, aiding reconstruction. NTFS does not mirror live records into unallocated space by design." },
  { id:70422, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the role of the GPT header found at LBA 1?", options:["It stores the operating system kernel that the firmware executes immediately after the power-on","It defines the partition entry array location, size, and a CRC to validate the table's integrity","It contains the user's full directory tree so the firmware can browse the files before booting up","It holds the BitLocker recovery keys for every encrypted partition described in the table itself"], correct:1, explanation:"The GPT header (LBA 1) locates the entry array and carries CRCs. It is not a kernel, directory tree, or key store." },
  { id:70423, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does a dd image (raw image) contain?", options:["Only the active files of the source, compressed into a proprietary container with added checksums","A list of file names and timestamps from the source, but none of the actual stored file content","An exact, uncompressed bit-for-bit copy of the source with no embedded metadata or any checksums","An encrypted snapshot of the source that requires the examiner's private key to open it up later"], correct:2, explanation:"A dd/raw image is an uncompressed bit-for-bit copy without embedded metadata. E01/AFF add metadata and checksums; raw does not." },
  { id:70424, domain:3, level:1, question:"What can examining browser cache and history on a disk image reveal?", options:["The full content of the suspect's encrypted email that is stored only on a remote mail server now","The cluster allocation table that NTFS uses internally to decide where to place any of new files","The firmware version of the hard drive that physically stored the browser's profile information","Visited sites, downloaded files, and timestamps that reconstruct a user's overall online activity"], correct:3, explanation:"Browser artifacts reveal visited sites, downloads, and times. They do not expose server-only email, the allocation table, or drive firmware." },
  { id:70425, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is a logical evidence file (e.g., L01) compared with a physical image?", options:["It stores selected files and folders with metadata rather than the entire raw disk surface itself","It stores the entire physical disk including slack, unlike a normal full bit-stream image would do","It is an encrypted wrapper that hides the file names from anyone who lacks the examiner's own key","It is a plain text report describing the case with no actual recovered files included in it at all"], correct:0, explanation:"An L01 holds selected files/folders with metadata, not the full raw disk. A physical image (E01/dd) captures the whole surface including slack." },
  { id:70426, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why is it important not to plug an unknown USB device directly into the analysis machine?", options:["The USB device will instantly format the analysis machine's primary system drive upon any contact","It could carry malware or alter the device, and it should be examined through a write blocker first","Connecting it permanently disables the analysis machine's network adapter for the security reasons overall","The device must first be heated to its operating temperature before any of the data can be read"], correct:1, explanation:"Unknown USB devices risk malware or alteration; use a write blocker. They do not auto-format the host, disable NICs, or need heating." },
  { id:70427, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the presence of multiple file systems on one disk image suggest to an examiner?", options:["The disk has failed and is reporting random garbage that should simply be ignored during analysis","The disk is encrypted end to end and cannot be imaged until the master key is first supplied here","The disk holds several partitions, each of which must be analyzed with the appropriate methods","The disk is a RAID member whose data is meaningless until the full array has been reassembled"], correct:2, explanation:"Multiple file systems usually mean multiple partitions, each analyzed appropriately. It does not by itself imply failure, whole-disk encryption, or RAID membership." },
  { id:70428, domain:3, level:2, question:"What forensic artifact does the Windows Recent folder of jump lists provide?", options:["A complete bit-for-bit backup of every single document the user has ever opened on the system now","The decryption keys for all of the BitLocker volumes that the user has unlocked in the recent past","The full network packet capture of all traffic the user generated during their recent sessions","A record of recently and frequently accessed files and applications tied to the user's account"], correct:3, explanation:"Jump lists evidence recently/frequently used files and apps. They are not full backups, key stores, or packet captures." },
  { id:70429, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the role of carving in unallocated space specifically?", options:["It targets areas no longer tracked by the file system to recover the deleted or any hidden files","It targets only the active files currently listed in the file system's main directory tree on disk","It targets the firmware region of the drive to extract the manufacturer's own diagnostic logs out","It targets the system RAM rather than the disk to recover the currently running program data now"], correct:0, explanation:"Carving unallocated space recovers deleted/hidden content the file system no longer tracks. It is not about active files, firmware, or RAM." },
  { id:70430, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why is a hash collision a theoretical concern when relying solely on MD5 for verification?", options:["MD5 changes the contents of the image each time it is computed, which corrupts the evidence file","Two different inputs could share an MD5 value, so stronger hashes like SHA-256 are now preferred","MD5 can only be calculated on FAT volumes, leaving NTFS and ext images entirely unverifiable now","MD5 encrypts the image, so the examiner can never read the verified contents again afterward at all"], correct:1, explanation:"MD5 collisions mean distinct inputs can share a hash, so SHA-256 is preferred. MD5 does not alter, restrict by file system, or encrypt the image." },
  { id:70431, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the ext file system's lost+found directory hold after a recovery check?", options:["A backup of the superblock that the kernel restores automatically when the volume is next mounted","The encryption keys for all of the user home directories on the Linux system that is being examined","Files and fragments whose directory links were lost, recovered by fsck for the later inspection","A continuous log of every command that the root user has executed on the live running machine"], correct:2, explanation:"lost+found holds orphaned files recovered by fsck. It is not a superblock backup, key store, or command log." },
  { id:70432, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is meant by a forensic duplicate being verified?", options:["Its file names have been alphabetized so that investigators can browse the evidence more easily overall","Its deleted files have all been permanently removed to protect the suspect's own privacy rights","Its size has been reduced through compression to fit it onto the examiner's very smallest media","Its hash equals the source's hash, proving that every bit was copied without any alteration at all"], correct:3, explanation:"A verified duplicate has a matching source hash, proving fidelity. Verification is unrelated to sorting names, removing files, or compression." },
  { id:70433, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why are shadow copies sometimes the only place to find a particular earlier file version?", options:["They snapshot the volume periodically, retaining states the user later overwrote or fully deleted","They store the live current version of every file, duplicating what is already present on the disk","They contain the encryption keys needed to read the rest of the files on that very same volume","They are the only structure that records the disk's physical sector and the cylinder geometry too"], correct:0, explanation:"Shadow copies retain periodic prior states, sometimes the only copy of overwritten data. They are not duplicates of current files, key stores, or geometry records." },
  { id:70434, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does block-level deduplication on a storage system mean for forensics?", options:["Every file is duplicated to a second block automatically so that no data can ever be lost at all","Identical blocks are stored once and referenced, so reconstructing a file may require following pointers","Each block is encrypted with a unique key derived from its physical position on the disk surface","Blocks are renamed sequentially, which conveniently removes all timestamps from the affected files overall"], correct:1, explanation:"Dedup stores identical blocks once with references, so files reconstruct via pointers. It is not duplication, per-block encryption, or timestamp removal." },
  { id:70435, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the typical first step when handling a suspect storage device in the lab?", options:["Immediately boot the device in its original computer to see exactly what files it contains inside","Format the device with the examiner's tools to ensure a clean and consistent file system layout","Document and photograph it, then create a verified forensic image before any of the examination","Run a defragmentation pass so the files become contiguous and much easier to analyze afterward"], correct:2, explanation:"First document and image the device before examination. Booting, formatting, or defragging the original would alter or destroy evidence." },
  { id:70436, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the forensic relevance of the NTFS $Secure metadata file?", options:["It contains the only copy of every user's password for the local accounts present on the machine","It holds a backup of all deleted files so they can be restored from a single central location later","It records the physical temperature of the drive each time that a file is written to the volume","It stores security descriptors, the permissions and ownership, shared by files across the volume"], correct:3, explanation:"$Secure stores shared security descriptors. It is not a password store, deleted-file backup, or temperature log." },
  { id:70437, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does it mean that NTFS is a journaling file system in recovery terms?", options:["Metadata operations are logged first, so an interrupted operation can be rolled back or completed","Every file's full content is journaled, so any deleted file can always be recovered fully intact","The journal encrypts the volume so that only the system service can read the protected files later","The journal stores the partition table so the disk layout survives even after a full disk wipe"], correct:0, explanation:"NTFS journals metadata first for crash consistency. It does not journal full content, encrypt the volume, or store the partition table." },
  { id:70438, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why might an investigator use timeline analysis across file system metadata?", options:["Ordering files alphabetically by name reveals exactly which user account created each of the files","Ordering events by MAC times helps reconstruct the sequence of user and the system activity here","Sorting by file size identifies which of the files are encrypted and which remain still in plaintext","Listing files by extension proves the exact moment the operating system was first installed on disk"], correct:1, explanation:"Timeline analysis orders MAC-time events to reconstruct activity. Alphabetical, size, or extension ordering does not establish event sequences." },
  { id:70439, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the impact of an examiner accidentally writing to evidence without a write blocker?", options:["The drive instantly becomes faster because the write optimizes the placement of the existing files","Nothing changes at all because operating systems never write to a drive that is only being read now","Timestamps and file system structures can change, undermining the integrity and the admissibility","The evidence becomes encrypted, which conveniently protects it from any further later tampering"], correct:2, explanation:"Unprotected writes can alter timestamps/structures, harming admissibility. OSes do write during mounting, and such writes do not optimize or encrypt evidence." },
  { id:70440, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the smallest unit the FAT file system allocates to a file?", options:["A single byte, allowing the file system to pack data with absolutely no wasted space whatsoever","A track, which spans an entire concentric ring across one surface of the spinning disk platter","A cylinder, which spans the same track position across every platter inside the drive all at once","A cluster, composed of one or more contiguous sectors as defined when the volume was formatted"], correct:3, explanation:"FAT allocates whole clusters (one or more sectors). Bytes, tracks, and cylinders are not allocation units in FAT." },
  { id:70441, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does the term volume serial number help an investigator do?", options:["Correlate a specific volume with shortcuts, logs, and other artifacts referencing that volume","Decrypt any BitLocker volume by feeding the serial number into the standard recovery algorithm","Determine the exact manufacturing date and the factory location of the physical hard drive unit","Recover deleted files by matching the serial against entries left in the recycle bin folder later"], correct:0, explanation:"The volume serial helps correlate artifacts (e.g., LNK files) to a volume. It does not decrypt BitLocker, reveal manufacturing data, or recover files." },
  { id:70442, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is a primary forensic concern with cloud-synced folders found on a disk?", options:["Cloud folders physically destroy the local data the instant the machine loses its internet link","Local copies may differ from cloud versions, and some data may exist only in the cloud account","Cloud folders are always fully encrypted locally with a key the examiner can never once recover","Cloud folders convert the entire disk to a proprietary file system unreadable by every known tool"], correct:1, explanation:"Local and cloud copies can diverge, and cloud-only data may exist. Cloud folders do not destroy local data, force whole-disk encryption, or change the file system." },
  { id:70443, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does carving recover that file-system-based recovery cannot when the file table is destroyed?", options:["Only the files whose names still appear intact in the file system's main directory listing here","Exclusively the files that the user has not yet moved into the recycle bin for later deletion now","Files reconstructed from raw content signatures even with no surviving directory or MFT entries","Just the partition table, which carving then rebuilds from the firmware of the disk drive itself"], correct:2, explanation:"Carving works from content signatures without any file table, unlike metadata-based recovery. It does not rely on names, the recycle bin, or firmware." },
  { id:70444, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why is examining the swap or page file relevant even when the disk is encrypted at rest?", options:["The page file is always stored unencrypted on a hidden second drive placed inside the computer","The page file contains the master decryption key for the volume in clear text at absolutely all times","The page file is the only file that survives a full-disk wipe of the encrypted system volume here","Once decrypted at runtime, the page file can hold plaintext fragments of the sensitive user data"], correct:3, explanation:"At runtime the decrypted page file may contain plaintext data fragments. It is not on a separate unencrypted drive, nor a guaranteed key or wipe-survivor." },
  { id:70445, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the role of hash verification after restoring an image to a new drive?", options:["Confirming the restored drive's hash matches the image proves the restoration was fully accurate","Confirming the new drive spins faster than the original validates that the restoration succeeded","Confirming the new drive has a different serial number proves it is a legitimate forensic copy here","Confirming the image shrank in size during restoration proves the compression worked correctly"], correct:0, explanation:"Matching hashes confirm an accurate restoration. Spin speed, serial number, and image size are irrelevant to verifying fidelity." },
  { id:70446, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does first responder documentation of storage devices typically include?", options:["A full forensic image of the device captured directly at the scene with no equipment at all needed","The device make, model, serial, the connection state, and its visible condition at the scene","The decrypted contents of every encrypted volume that is present on the seized storage device now","A guaranteed list of every deleted file the device has ever contained since its manufacture date"], correct:1, explanation:"First responders document make, model, serial, state, and condition. They do not magically image, decrypt, or enumerate all deleted files on site." },
  { id:70447, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why are allocation algorithms relevant to predicting where deleted data may survive?", options:["Allocation algorithms encrypt freed clusters immediately, so deleted data never survives at all","Allocation algorithms determine the spin speed of the disk and thus how fast the data is erased","How a file system reuses freed clusters affects how long deleted data persists before overwrite","Allocation algorithms apply only to RAM, so they have no bearing on disk-based deleted data here"], correct:2, explanation:"Cluster reuse strategy affects how long deleted data lingers. Allocation does not encrypt freed clusters, set spin speed, or apply only to RAM." },
  { id:70448, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the forensic significance of b-tree structures in NTFS directory indexing?", options:["They store the full content of every file in the directory for the fast retrieval by the system","They encrypt directory listings so only the file owner can see which files a given folder contains","They keep a backup of the partition table so the disk can be remounted after a corruption event","They organize directory entries for efficient lookup, and their slack can retain deleted entries"], correct:3, explanation:"B-tree indexes order directory entries and may retain deleted entries in slack. They do not store file content, encrypt listings, or back up the partition table." },
  { id:70449, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does metadata carving specifically attempt to recover?", options:["File system structures like the MFT entries or inodes to rebuild names, sizes, and timestamps","Only the raw pixel data of images, ignoring any names, sizes, or the timestamp information at all","The encryption keys embedded in the file system superblock for unlocking the whole volume later","The electrical signals on the disk bus captured while the suspect machine was running live at scene"], correct:0, explanation:"Metadata carving recovers structures (MFT entries, inodes) to rebuild file metadata. It is not pixel-only carving, key extraction, or bus capture." },
  { id:70450, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the function of a write-blocking software driver compared with a hardware blocker?", options:["It physically cuts the write pins on the drive cable, which is identical to the hardware approach","It intercepts write commands at the OS level, but relies on the OS, so hardware is more trusted","It encrypts every write that the OS attempts so the data on the source drive cannot be altered","It speeds up reads by caching the source drive contents into the analysis workstation's memory"], correct:1, explanation:"Software blockers intercept writes via the OS but depend on it; hardware blockers are more trusted. It does not cut pins, encrypt, or cache for speed." },
  { id:70451, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the relevance of the NTFS $Boot metadata file?", options:["It stores a backup of every user's password hash for the local accounts present on the machine now","It records a complete log of every file that has been deleted from the volume since formatting time","It contains the volume boot record and parameters the system uses to begin loading from the volume","It holds the BitLocker recovery key that is required to unlock the encrypted system volume at boot"], correct:2, explanation:"$Boot holds the VBR and boot parameters. It is not a password store, deletion log, or BitLocker key holder." },
  { id:70452, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why can examining $MFT entry attributes reveal whether a file was resident or non-resident?", options:["Resident files are always encrypted, while non-resident files are always stored fully in plaintext","Resident files appear only in RAM, while non-resident files appear only on the physical disk surface","Resident files are larger than the volume, while non-resident files are smaller than one cluster","Resident data sits inside the record, while non-resident data uses data runs pointing to clusters"], correct:3, explanation:"The attribute's resident flag and data runs distinguish in-record storage from cluster storage. Residency is about size/location, not encryption, RAM, or impossible sizes." },
  { id:70453, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is slack space carving able to recover that ordinary file carving may overlook?", options:["Remnants of a previous file hiding in the tail of a cluster now reused by a smaller current file","The complete and current contents of every active file that is presently allocated on the volume","The encryption keys that the operating system stores inside each cluster's reserved header area","The exact spin speed history of the drive recorded in the unused tail bytes of every cluster"], correct:0, explanation:"Slack carving targets old-file remnants in reused cluster tails. It does not recover current files, keys, or drive telemetry." },
  { id:70454, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does the presence of a swap partition on a Linux disk offer an investigator?", options:["A complete and current copy of the entire root file system kept for redundancy against failure","Potential memory remnants such as decrypted data, keys, or process information paged out to disk","The encryption passphrase for the whole disk stored permanently at the start of the swap area","A chronological log of every user command that the shell has executed since the last system boot"], correct:1, explanation:"Swap can hold paged-out memory remnants (keys, data). It is not a root-fs copy, a passphrase store, or a command log." },
  { id:70455, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is verifying a forensic image with two different hash algorithms sometimes recommended?", options:["Two algorithms are required because a single algorithm cannot process drives larger than two terabytes","Two algorithms encrypt the image twice, doubling the protection against unauthorized later access","Using two algorithms greatly reduces the chance an undetected collision masks any data alteration","Two algorithms are needed so the image can be opened on both Windows and Linux analysis machines"], correct:2, explanation:"Two hashes reduce the chance a collision hides tampering. It is not about drive size limits, encryption, or cross-platform compatibility." },
  { id:70456, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the significance of a partition's starting offset when carving a file system?", options:["The starting offset is the decryption key for the partition's encrypted contents on the volume here","The starting offset records the timestamp at which the partition was first created by the installer","The starting offset lists every deleted file's original location within that particular partition","Tools must know where the partition begins so they correctly parse the file system structures there"], correct:3, explanation:"The starting offset lets tools locate and parse the file system. It is not a key, creation timestamp, or deleted-file index." },
  { id:70457, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does the term over-provisioning describe on an SSD that matters to forensics?", options:["Reserved spare flash, hidden from the host, that the controller uses for wear leveling and may hold data","A second visible partition that the operating system always mounts for storing the user's backups overall","An encrypted region containing the recovery keys for every other block written onto the drive","A diagnostic log partition the host can read to see every write the drive has ever performed"], correct:0, explanation:"Over-provisioning is hidden spare flash for wear leveling that may retain data inaccessible to the host. It is not a visible partition, key store, or readable log." },
  { id:70458, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is acquiring a memory image important for investigating in-memory-only malware?", options:["Such malware always writes itself to the MBR, so only imaging the first disk sector reveals it now","Such malware may never touch the disk, so only a RAM capture preserves the evidence of it running","Such malware encrypts the whole disk, so the RAM image is needed to obtain the decryption key first","Such malware deletes the page file, so the RAM image is the only place its configuration survives"], correct:1, explanation:"Fileless malware lives in RAM, so a memory image captures it. It does not necessarily touch the MBR, encrypt the disk, or delete the page file." },
  { id:70459, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the role of the partition table in directing a forensic tool to file systems?", options:["It stores the decrypted contents of each partition so tools can read files without any further work","It contains a full backup of each partition's MFT so deleted files are always trivially recovered","It records each partition's type, start, and size so tools mount the correct file system parser","It holds the user's passwords so the analysis tool can authenticate to each encrypted partition"], correct:2, explanation:"The partition table describes type, start, and size so tools parse correctly. It does not store decrypted content, MFT backups, or passwords." },
  { id:70460, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why might an examiner recover and analyze the Windows SAM and SYSTEM registry hives?", options:["They contain a complete bit-for-bit image of the system disk for redundancy against any failure","They store every document the user has ever created in a single compressed registry container","They hold the partition table so the disk layout can be rebuilt after a severe corruption event","They contain account information and the keys needed to extract stored local password hashes"], correct:3, explanation:"SAM/SYSTEM hold account data and keys to extract local hashes. They are not a disk image, document store, or partition table." },
  { id:70461, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does carving based on a file's footer signature help determine?", options:["The end of a recovered file, so the carver knows where the data stops and avoids overrun bytes","The encryption strength applied to the file, so the carver can request the correct decryption key","The exact user account that created the file, so the carver can attribute it during the analysis","The physical disk temperature when the file was written, so the carver can date the file precisely"], correct:0, explanation:"A footer signature marks where a file ends, bounding the carve. It does not reveal encryption, the creating user, or drive temperature." },
  { id:70462, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why is the integrity of the chain of custody essential for digital evidence?", options:["Gaps automatically encrypt the evidence drive so investigators can no longer access the file content","Gaps can let opposing counsel argue the evidence was altered, threatening its admissibility in court","Gaps cause the forensic image to compress incorrectly, making the recovered files unreadable later","Gaps reset every file's MAC timestamps to zero, which destroys the timeline analysis evidence used"], correct:1, explanation:"Custody gaps invite claims of tampering and risk admissibility. Gaps do not encrypt, compress, or reset timestamps on the evidence." },
  { id:70463, domain:3, level:1, question:"What is the value of analyzing the Windows event logs found on a disk image?", options:["They contain the decrypted content of every file the user opened during each logged-in session","They store the master file table so deleted files can be enumerated directly from the log entries","They record logons, system events, and other activity that help reconstruct the timeline of use","They hold the BitLocker keys needed to mount the encrypted volume during the later examination"], correct:2, explanation:"Event logs record logons and system activity for timeline work. They are not a file-content store, the MFT, or a key vault." },
  { id:70464, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why does imaging an SSD twice sometimes produce two different hash values?", options:["The imaging tool deliberately corrupts random sectors during each pass to test its own reliability","The drive encrypts its contents with a fresh key on every read, altering the resulting hash value","The SSD physically shrinks in capacity each time it is imaged, which changes the computed hash","Background garbage collection and TRIM can change unallocated blocks between the two acquisitions"], correct:3, explanation:"SSD internal activity (GC, TRIM) can alter blocks between images, changing hashes. The drive does not corrupt sectors, re-key per read, or shrink." },
  { id:70465, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the forensic relevance of NTFS object IDs ($ObjId)?", options:["They can link files across copies and locations, helping track a file even after it has been moved","They contain the only stored copy of each file's content for redundancy against any disk failure","They record the disk's physical geometry so tools can compute cylinder and head positions exactly overall","They store the encryption keys that protect the file from being read by an unauthorized account"], correct:0, explanation:"$ObjId tracks files via unique object identifiers, useful across moves/copies. It is not content storage, geometry, or a key store." },
  { id:70466, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why should an examiner note the firmware and model of a drive during acquisition?", options:["The firmware model is the decryption key required to read any encrypted partitions on the drive","Certain firmware quirks and HPA or DCO features affect how completely the drive can be imaged","The model number records the exact timestamps of every file ever written to the drive over time","The firmware contains a full backup of the partition table that must be restored before imaging"], correct:1, explanation:"Firmware/model can reveal HPA/DCO behavior affecting full acquisition. The model is not a decryption key, timestamp record, or partition-table backup." },
  { id:70467, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does analyzing file system metadata timestamps across many files allow an investigator to build?", options:["A complete decrypted copy of each file's content reconstructed solely from the timestamp values","An exact map of the disk's bad sectors derived from comparing every file's recorded access time","A timeline of activity showing when files were created, modified, and accessed on the system","A list of the network addresses that connected to the machine during each recorded file access"], correct:2, explanation:"Metadata timestamps across files build an activity timeline. They do not yield file content, a bad-sector map, or network addresses." },
  { id:70468, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of the boot.ini or BCD store in Windows boot forensics?", options:["It stores a full backup of the master file table so deleted files can be enumerated from the store","It contains the decryption keys for the BitLocker-protected volume read by the loader at boot time","It records every user logon to the machine along with the precise timestamp of each access event","It defines boot configuration and which OS or partition the loader starts, evidencing system setup"], correct:3, explanation:"boot.ini (legacy) and BCD describe boot configuration and OS selection. They are not the MFT, BitLocker keys, or a logon log." },
  { id:70469, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does a degausser do to a magnetic hard drive?", options:["It applies a strong magnetic field that erases the data and usually renders the drive unusable","It overwrites every sector with random data while leaving the drive fully functional for reuse","It encrypts the platters so that only the original owner with the key can later read the data","It physically shreds the platters into fragments no larger than a couple of millimeters across"], correct:0, explanation:"A degausser erases magnetically and typically ruins the drive. It is not overwriting, encryption, or physical shredding (that is 'destroy')." },
  { id:70470, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why is solid-state drive data not erasable by a magnetic degausser?", options:["SSDs spin too fast for the degausser's field to penetrate the platters during the erase cycle","SSDs store data as charge in NAND flash cells, which a magnetic field does not affect at all","SSDs encrypt every cell, so the degausser scrambles only the ciphertext and leaves the plaintext","SSDs store data optically, so only a laser, not a magnet, can overwrite the recorded information"], correct:1, explanation:"SSDs use NAND charge storage, immune to magnetic fields. They have no platters, and the magnetic-immunity is about the storage medium, not encryption or optics." },
  { id:70471, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is a forensic concern when a drive reports a smaller capacity than its label states?", options:["The drive is simply failing and any data it still holds should be ignored during the examination","The reported capacity is the decryption key length, which the examiner needs to unlock the data","A hidden HPA or DCO may be concealing data, so the examiner should detect and access it first","The mismatch proves the drive was already securely wiped, so no further analysis is required at all"], correct:2, explanation:"A capacity mismatch can signal a hidden HPA/DCO holding data. It is not a failure to ignore, a key length, or proof of wiping." },
  { id:70472, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the ext4 journal record to aid crash recovery and forensics?", options:["A complete second copy of every file written to the volume for redundancy against disk failure overall","The encryption passphrase for the whole volume so the kernel can mount it after a system crash","The physical geometry of the disk so the kernel can recompute sector positions after any crash","Metadata, or optionally data, changes pending commit, leaving a trail of recent file operations"], correct:3, explanation:"The ext4 journal logs pending metadata (or data) changes, revealing recent operations. It is not a full file copy, passphrase, or geometry record." },
  { id:70473, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why might a forensic examiner mount a disk image using a loopback device on Linux?", options:["To access the file systems inside the image read-only without altering the original evidence file","To compress the image so that it occupies far less space on the examiner's workstation storage overall","To permanently delete any malware from the image before the analysis of the contents begins","To convert the image into a proprietary format that only the examiner's own tools can read"], correct:0, explanation:"Loopback mounting (read-only) exposes the image's file systems without altering evidence. It is not compression, malware removal, or format conversion." },
  { id:70474, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the relevance of the recycle bin INFO2 file on older Windows systems?", options:["It stores a full copy of each deleted file's content so the bin can restore them at any time","It records original paths, deletion times, and indexes for files moved into the recycle bin","It contains the partition table for the disk that holds the recycle bin on the affected system","It holds the user password needed to empty the recycle bin and permanently remove the files"], correct:1, explanation:"INFO2 indexes deleted files with original paths and times. It is not a content store, partition table, or password holder." },
  { id:70475, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does carving for email artifacts such as PST or OST files help recover?", options:["The live network credentials the mail client used to authenticate to the remote mail server","The encryption keys that protect every other file stored on the same volume as the mailbox","Stored mailbox data including messages and attachments even when the file is partly deleted","The partition table of the disk on which the mailbox file was originally created by the client"], correct:2, explanation:"Carving PST/OST recovers mailbox messages and attachments. It does not yield network credentials, volume keys, or the partition table." },
  { id:70476, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is the $Extend\\$UsnJrnl change journal often analyzed in intrusion cases?", options:["It stores the attacker's source IP address for every file that the attacker touched on the system","It contains a full decrypted copy of every file the attacker accessed during the intrusion event","It holds the attacker's login password in plaintext, recovered directly from the journal records","It can show files created, deleted, or renamed by an attacker, helping reconstruct their actions"], correct:3, explanation:"The USN journal logs file create/delete/rename events, reconstructing attacker activity. It is not an IP log, content copy, or password store." },
  { id:70477, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the forensic value of analyzing shellbags in the Windows registry?", options:["They record folders a user browsed in Explorer, evidencing access even to since-deleted folders","They store the full content of every folder the user opened so the data can later be recovered overall","They contain the cluster allocation map that NTFS uses to place new files on the disk volume","They hold the BitLocker recovery key for every encrypted volume the user opened in Explorer"], correct:0, explanation:"Shellbags evidence browsed folders, including deleted ones. They are not a content store, allocation map, or key vault." },
  { id:70478, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does the term file system tunneling affect in NTFS timestamp forensics?", options:["Tunneling encrypts the file's timestamps so that only the system service can read them correctly","A recreated file may inherit the prior file's creation time, which can mislead timeline analysis","Tunneling permanently deletes a file's timestamps the moment the file is removed from the volume","Tunneling copies a file's timestamps into the page file for safekeeping during a system shutdown"], correct:1, explanation:"Tunneling can cause a recreated file to inherit an old creation time, misleading timelines. It is not timestamp encryption, deletion, or page-file copying." },
  { id:70479, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is examining the MFT $FILE_NAME creation time useful against timestomping?", options:["It contains the only copy of the file's content, which the investigator can recover from the time","It stores the decryption key for the file in the low bits of the recorded creation timestamp value","It is harder for common tools to alter than $STANDARD_INFORMATION, so it can expose tampering","It records the IP address of the host that last modified the file's timestamps over the network"], correct:2, explanation:"$FILE_NAME timestamps resist common timestomping tools, helping detect tampering. They are not content, a key, or a network log." },
  { id:70480, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the role of a forensic bridge (e.g., a USB write-blocking bridge)?", options:["It permanently encrypts the suspect drive as soon as it is connected to the examiner's machine","It reformats the suspect drive into a universal file system before the imaging process begins","It deletes any malware from the suspect drive automatically before the examiner reads the data","It connects a suspect drive to the workstation while blocking writes to preserve the evidence"], correct:3, explanation:"A forensic bridge provides write-blocked connectivity. It does not encrypt, reformat, or clean the suspect drive." },
  { id:70481, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does analyzing the Windows AmCache or ShimCache reveal in execution forensics?", options:["Evidence that specific executables were present or run, including paths and some timestamps","A complete decrypted copy of every program the user ran during each logged-in session on disk","The cluster allocation table NTFS uses internally to place each executable file onto the volume","The user's account password, recovered directly from the cache entries left by the application"], correct:0, explanation:"AmCache/ShimCache evidence program presence/execution with paths and times. They are not content copies, allocation tables, or password stores." },
  { id:70482, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why is it important to image the entire physical disk rather than only a single partition?", options:["A partition image is always corrupted, so only a full physical image can ever be read by any tool","Data may reside in unpartitioned space, other partitions, or hidden areas missed by a partition image","Imaging one partition automatically encrypts the others, making the remaining data unrecoverable","A physical image is required because partitions cannot be hashed for integrity verification at all overall"], correct:1, explanation:"A full physical image captures unpartitioned and hidden areas a partition image would miss. Partition images are valid and hashable; imaging one does not encrypt others." },
  { id:70483, domain:3, level:1, question:"What does the presence of a BitLocker recovery key in Active Directory mean for an investigator?", options:["The volume is automatically decrypted the moment the machine joins the corporate domain network","The key in the directory is a decoy, so the real key must always be extracted from the system RAM","The encrypted volume may be unlocked using the escrowed key obtained from the directory service","The escrowed key encrypts the directory itself, so it cannot be used to unlock any disk volume"], correct:2, explanation:"An AD-escrowed recovery key can unlock the BitLocker volume. Joining a domain does not auto-decrypt, and the escrowed key is genuine, not a decoy." },
  { id:70484, domain:3, level:1, question:"Why are file signatures preferred over file extensions when classifying recovered files?", options:["Extensions are encrypted by the file system, while header bytes are always stored in plaintext form","Extensions exist only in RAM, while header bytes are the only file information written to the disk","Extensions are unique per user, while header bytes are shared by every file on the entire volume","Extensions are easily renamed, while header bytes more reliably reveal the file's actual true type"], correct:3, explanation:"Renaming an extension is trivial, but header signatures reveal true type. Extensions are not encrypted, RAM-only, or per-user." },
  { id:70485, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the significance of the $J data stream within the NTFS USN journal?", options:["It holds the actual change records describing file and directory modifications on the volume","It stores a full content backup of every file changed since the volume was first formatted","It contains the encryption keys for each modified file so they can be re-encrypted on demand","It records the spinning speed of the drive at the moment each change was made to a given file"], correct:0, explanation:"$J holds the USN change records. It is not a content backup, key store, or drive-speed log." },
  { id:70486, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why might an examiner recover Volume Shadow Copies to find deleted files?", options:["Shadow copies are the only structure that stores the current live version of each file on the disk","A shadow copy may retain a file that was deleted from the live volume after the snapshot was taken","Shadow copies contain the encryption keys required to read the rest of the files on that volume","Shadow copies record the disk's physical geometry needed to locate each deleted file precisely"], correct:1, explanation:"A shadow copy can hold a file later deleted from the live volume. They are not live-version stores, key vaults, or geometry records." },
  { id:70487, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does the term carving with validation mean in advanced file recovery?", options:["The carver encrypts each recovered file so that only the examiner can open the recovered content","The carver deletes any recovered file that does not match a known hash in the examiner's database","The carver checks recovered data against format rules to confirm the file is valid and complete","The carver renames every recovered file using the original name read from the file system metadata"], correct:2, explanation:"Validation confirms a carved file conforms to its format. It is not encryption, hash-based deletion, or metadata-based renaming." },
  { id:70488, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why is the slack of the last MFT record cluster of forensic interest?", options:["It always stores the live copy of the volume's partition table for quick mounting at boot time","It holds the BitLocker recovery key required to unlock the encrypted volume during examination","It records the disk temperature each time the MFT is written, useful for dating file operations","It may contain remnants of previously deleted MFT entries, helping reconstruct removed files"], correct:3, explanation:"MFT slack can retain old deleted MFT entries aiding reconstruction. It is not a partition-table, key, or temperature store." },
  { id:70489, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is a key reason to use a forensic boot environment such as a live Linux distribution?", options:["It boots without mounting the suspect drive writable, preserving the evidence during examination","It automatically decrypts every encrypted volume on the suspect drive before the analysis begins","It permanently wipes the suspect drive after imaging to ensure the data cannot be misused later","It converts the suspect drive's file system into a universal format readable by every known tool"], correct:0, explanation:"A forensic live environment avoids writing to the suspect drive. It does not auto-decrypt, wipe, or convert the file system." },
  { id:70490, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why do investigators document the SHA-256 hash of each acquired image in the case notes?", options:["It serves as the decryption key that the examiner must enter to open the image in any analysis tool","It provides a tamper-evident fingerprint proving the image is unchanged from acquisition onward","It compresses the image so the recorded hash takes less space than the full evidence file would","It encrypts the case notes so that only investigators with the hash can read the documentation"], correct:1, explanation:"A recorded hash is a tamper-evident fingerprint for integrity. It is not a decryption key, compression, or note encryption." },
  { id:70491, domain:3, level:2, question:"What does analyzing the $T attribute or transaction logs ($TxfLog) on NTFS support?", options:["Storing the complete content of every file ever changed by a transaction for later full recovery","Holding the encryption keys for files modified within a transaction so they can be re-encrypted","Recovering details of transactional file operations, which can reveal recent changes to files","Recording the IP address of every host that initiated a transactional write over the network share"], correct:2, explanation:"TxF logs detail transactional file operations, revealing recent changes. They are not content stores, key vaults, or network IP logs." },
  { id:70492, domain:3, level:2, question:"Why is write-once media such as a CD-R sometimes used to store forensic evidence copies?", options:["It automatically encrypts the evidence so that only the original examiner can ever read it back","It compresses the evidence far more efficiently than any hard drive could possibly achieve now","It allows the evidence to be edited repeatedly while keeping a log of every change that is made","Its data cannot be altered after burning, supporting the integrity of the stored evidence copy"], correct:3, explanation:"Write-once media resists later alteration, aiding integrity. It does not auto-encrypt, compress better, or allow repeated edits." },
  { id:70493, domain:3, level:2, question:"What is the forensic relevance of the pagefile being clearable on shutdown via policy?", options:["If a system clears the page file at shutdown, in-memory remnants may be lost to the examiner","Clearing the page file automatically encrypts the entire disk so the data becomes unrecoverable","Clearing the page file copies all of its contents into the registry for later safekeeping there","Clearing the page file rebuilds the master file table, which then exposes every deleted file"], correct:0, explanation:"A cleared page file destroys memory remnants an examiner might want. It does not encrypt the disk, copy to the registry, or rebuild the MFT." },
  { id:70494, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why might examining the LNK file's embedded volume serial number be useful?", options:["It contains the full content of the target file so the original can be recovered from the shortcut","It can tie a shortcut to a specific removable or fixed volume, evidencing where a file resided","It stores the user's password so the system can reopen the target without prompting for credentials","It records the exact spin speed of the drive that held the target file when the shortcut was made"], correct:1, explanation:"The LNK volume serial links a shortcut to a specific volume. It is not target content, a password, or drive-speed data." },
  { id:70495, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does analyzing the registry USBSTOR key reveal in device forensics?", options:["The full content of every file ever copied from a USB device onto the local machine's hard disk","The encryption key for any BitLocker volume that was unlocked using an external USB key device","A history of USB storage devices connected to the machine, including vendor and serial details","The cluster allocation map NTFS used to store data copied from each connected USB storage device"], correct:2, explanation:"USBSTOR records connected USB storage devices with identifiers. It is not a file-content store, key vault, or allocation map." },
  { id:70496, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is acquiring a hash of the source while it is still write-blocked considered sound practice?", options:["Hashing through a write blocker doubles the cryptographic strength of the resulting hash value","The write blocker compresses the source so the hash can be computed far more quickly than usual overall","Hashing a write-blocked drive encrypts it, which protects the evidence from any later tampering","The write block guarantees the source is unchanged, so the hash reflects the true original state"], correct:3, explanation:"A write-blocked hash captures the genuine unaltered source state. Write blocking does not strengthen the hash, compress, or encrypt the drive." },
  { id:70497, domain:3, level:3, question:"What does the presence of carved file fragments without footers usually indicate?", options:["The file may be incomplete or fragmented, so the recovered data should be validated carefully","The file is fully encrypted, so the missing footer is simply the result of the encryption process","The file was created on an SSD, where footers are never written by the controller to any block","The file belongs to the operating system, which always omits footers from its own system files"], correct:0, explanation:"Missing footers suggest incomplete or fragmented files needing validation. It is not inherently due to encryption, SSDs, or OS file conventions." },
  { id:70498, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why is the reserved area at the start of an NTFS volume ($Boot and metadata files) examined?", options:["They contain a full decrypted copy of every user file for redundancy against any disk failure event","These structures define the volume layout and can reveal tampering or corruption to an examiner","They store the user's login password in plaintext so the system can authenticate them at boot time","They record the network addresses of every host that has ever connected to the machine over time"], correct:1, explanation:"NTFS metadata files define layout and can show tampering/corruption. They are not user-file copies, password stores, or network logs." },
  { id:70499, domain:3, level:3, question:"What is the forensic benefit of analyzing both the live system and a forensic image together?", options:["The live system automatically decrypts the image, removing the need for any recovery key at all","Analyzing both compresses the evidence so it takes much less storage on the examiner's machine","Volatile evidence from the live system complements the persistent evidence preserved in the image","The live system rewrites the image to repair any corrupted sectors before the analysis can begin overall"], correct:2, explanation:"Combining live (volatile) and image (persistent) evidence gives a fuller picture. It does not auto-decrypt, compress, or repair the image." },
  { id:70500, domain:3, level:3, question:"Why might a forensic examiner calculate per-sector hashes during acquisition?", options:["To encrypt each sector individually so that the resulting image cannot be read without a key set","To compress each sector so the overall image fits on the smallest possible piece of backup media","To rename each sector sequentially so that deleted files become trivially easy to recover later","To localize exactly where any corruption occurs if the overall image hash later fails to verify"], correct:3, explanation:"Per-sector hashing pinpoints where corruption occurs on verification failure. It is not encryption, compression, or sector renaming." },
];
